text: Ok...first thoughts... Nice cinematography and set design, amazing soundtrack and music  The acting as always gets a “good job”  Personal opinion: Make up your mind Disney!!!!!   In the original Maleficent she was all good as a child but understandingly she turned evil but then you turned her good because she loved Aurora, a misunderstood being whom we understood at the beginning but her character didn’t fit with the ending on the original movie...in my opinion... Now your telling me she is evil just because!?!?!?!  Your character is so inconsistent now, in the original ending we saw Maleficent approve Aurora’s relationship with the prince because she smiled when she saw them together  Are you seriously telling me she didn’t expect them to marry????  Oh wow Maleficent, you are going to FORCE Aurora to live with you under your unexpected tyrannical rule just because?!?!? As far I recall, you gave her a choice in the previous movie Now I know it’s a “maternal” characteristic but come on, it’s not like this...you should expect Aurora to visit her human world because she is HUMAN! Then she says “Love doesn’t end well...” REALLY?!?!? You used love to save Aurora on the last film! How could you say it doesn’t work?!?!  Then like a child in a tantrum, she attacks and provokes the war with another kingdom...wow! Really wise and mature Maleficent... now when the queen whom is the “villain” in this story says “Aurora is now my own...” I believe she meant it as “she is my daughter in law, she is my family now too” But of course it’s another misunderstanding story where Maleficent literally provoked and caused Everything to go wrong ... yep, predictable.  If I were Aurora, I would leave Maleficent, Maleficent hasn’t done anything but trouble after I was born and cursed lol and then she killed my father , and now wants to stop my wedding? Ha. Yep leave that crazy witch behind and live with your husband!  You can’t have this character be good here and at the same time be the mistress of all evil from the animated movie... This character MUST be identical or completely different, you can’t have both, you must take a side  My personal evil woman character of all time will always be the animated Maleficent.  Finally, the twist...there are more of her...this is the cherry in the cake that made me give up on this movie... this scene is a little interesting but it proves and reveals that Maleficent isn’t alone but also it doesn’t make Maleficent Special anymore, she won’t stand out anymore, she won’t be known as the mistress of all evil anymore, why?!?!? Because she shares her power and/or she has a decency of evil mistresses and misters ... she won’t be the ONLY one ... thought that was the orinal intent, she was the only mistress of all evil! Now it’s ruined ... This new one has so many inconsistencies and can’t make up her mind.  I might give the movie a watch if it’s for free...

text: Disney remakes should go on this way. It's frustrated to see they bring every cartoon version without changing or adding something fresh to the screen.       I support Disney to try to create new plot, hidden stories like they already done well with maleficent. Or turn the old, original path to unexpected direction like the Mulan movie upcoming. They should take a look into once upon a time and perhaps learn from it.      I watched OUAT and it's good despite the messed up in those final seasons, it's sad that the series has ended. To be honest, it's quite...speechless at first, seeing Snow white, evil queen and other fairy tale characters are far from the original models. Even the same scenarios, main events are still here but it's just entire different stories to tell.       It's challenging, yep, for kids and adults like me to accept if the entire classical stories change. But for the long run, I suggest Disney to take the risk and...innovate.       People already complained a lot about the milking and the "nostalgic but boring", full of cgi movies. Perhaps it should be ended and move to new phrase.

text: I am... confused. I thought this version of Maleficent was a bit in the grey area of evil, but otherwise a heroine. Now she’s just full-on evil? Why? How? Because Michelle Pfeiffer claimed Aurora as her own? That’s... not exactly what I gained from the first one. Shouldn’t it be Pfeiffer who’s the villain, by the own rules of the last movie? Logically, this film shouldn’t make sense, just by the title alone. And bear in mind, this is coming from someone who LIKED the first movie.  Okay, based on a second viewing, I think I noticed something. Maleficent isn’t the villain; Pfeiffer is. Her ‘caring’ for Aurora while smirking during the hug? That’s something a VILLAIN does. I’m legitimately hoping we’ll get more of Maleficent being powerful and terrifying (more than the first), but I bet she’ll become a heroine again.

(She finds every Disney princess from each of there time periods)  Jasmine, Aladdin — c. 300s Arabian Peninsula  Aurora, Sleeping Beauty — c. 1300s England  Snow White, Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs — c. mid- to late 1500s Germany  Pocahontas, Pocahontas — c. early 1600s Virginia  Belle, Beauty and the Beast — c. 1700s France  Tiana, The Princess and the Frog — c. 1920s New Orleans  ECT.  By the time she got back from her meeting with her royal family, everything was normal at first. Her 18-year old brother asked what happened, by the time she told the truth her older brother described it was a huge mistake, because if a person meets past ancestors carelessly and without understanding could create an altar in the space-time continuum, getting rid of the past itself and transporting it into our current time. text: Was anyone asking for this? I don't mind that they took Maleficent in a different direction in these movies, as I'm a proponent of the idea of only remaking something if you want to do something different with it. But it's the way they changed it that bothers me, not the fact that it's different at all. Taking one of the best Disney villains of all time and degrading her to the status of a clingy foster mother for Aurora who has trust issues is borderline insulting to one of Disney's most iconic characters. You can change her without making her uninteresting. No disrespect to the talented cast and crew who put all their work into this, but I think I'll pass.

I am sure they might not blatantly say this in the film, but it would be obvious he has political rule now over her lands.    I mean why on Earth would Philips mother want a newly crowned Queen for her son, who has been living outside of court all this time so does not understand the intricacies of politics. text: Honestly this debate over good or evil is stupid to me. She's flawed. No one is one or the other. If someone does bad there is usually a reason that leads up to it whether we feel it's justified or not. A villain being evil "just because" is boring as hell. Having her trust broken. Feeling betrayed and hurt and lashing out because of it. These actions make more sense to me and makes her character and anger more believable. If you want a 2d character villain with an oversimplified plot, go watch the cartoon to relive your missed childhood and leave this movie to the adults. From the trailer, I'm on Team Maleficent. She may have overreacted but she had justification to be offended by that lady's backhanded comments. ( I will say that I feel she could have cut that bitch up one side and down the other with her words alone rather than getting physical though.) Just because Aurora was too stupid to notice doesn't change the fact that it was an insult. Honestly I feel like she should have been at a children's table or something and left the adults to their business. She is so boring as a character. She supposedly sees Mal as a mother but is okay with the way that woman treated her. If that was me and my mom, I'd be the first one defending her even though I know she wouldn't need me to. Makes me want to smack her.

text: I’m sorry; this just looks trite. What’s wrong with having a genuinely evil character just be genuinely evil? Why do we need to be sympathetic towards them? The first Maleficent movie ruined the character for me, and just felt like needless pandering for the sake of making a quick buck off Hot Topic customers. They could have made a mature version of Sleeping Beauty, while keeping Maleficent as the female embodiment of pure magical evil, expand upon Aurora’s family and the Prince’s, and give a more compelling story than what we got in the animation. “Maleficent” made the Fairies irrelevant. They dumbed down the gravity of Maleficent‘s curse and her sociopathic pettiness over not being invited. It’s supposed to show how petty and cruel she is, and make her to be this purely evil, yet cunning and methodical villain. Instead we get a dumbed down curse, irrelevant fairies, and even worse; MALEFICENT CARES ABOUT AURORA!! She’s supposed to want her dead, and only the intervention of the last fairy’s blessing lessens the toll from death to sleep. Gods above and below, this is just ridiculous.
author: Oisín Lee Foraois

text: Sooooo this is kind of dumb. Not the idea of her turning evil again. Just how they do it. So Maleficent disapproves of Arura getting married? That’s fine and fits her character considering her relationship history. Getting mad that someone considers her a monster unfit to be a humans mother, also understandable. Her waging war on the kingdom whose queen (and seemingly ONLY it’s queen) insulted her because her “Daughter” is going to marry that kingdoms prince? That’s just kind of dumb. While yes the queen insulted her, she does remember she kind of went evil for awhile (for partially justifiable reasons) right? I just find it dumb that THIS is what turns her evil. There are probably a million other ways you can do this. Maybe the person Arura did marry after years of being married to Arura decided to separate magic from the kingdom due to multiple events which were caused through magical actions. You can even have Arura partially agree and have Maleficent feel betrayed which leads her down a dark path.

text: You know, technically, Maleficent is the villain. She does violent things out of anger, her first instinct is to fight back, she’s crazy overprotective that it can be unreasonable. And if this were in the point of view of the other kingdom, we’d all see her as the villain. But, hear me out before you start bashing me. She’s the type of villain you can understand. The type of villain who is the way she is for a good reason. We just needed to hear her side of the story, which we did. A lot of us could probably relate to her. the last film stated she’s a villain and a hero. Which makes complete sense. she’s not doing this for dominance or power, or for chaos. she’s doing it because she’s hurt and wants to prove a point. She made a promise to Aurora that she’d protect her for the rest of her life and she’s keeping to that promise. Maleficent is literally the perfect example of a loving mother who wants the best for her child.  Everything she does is just an example of how much she cares.
